SiteDescription:
The Royal London Hospital is home to one of the largest children’s hospitals in the UK with one of London's busiest paediatric accident and emergency departments.

It is also home to London’s Air Ambulance service and one of the capital's leading trauma and emergency care centres and hyper-acute stroke centres.

The Breathe London Node is located near the entrance to A&E to assess the exposure of visitors, patients and staff at the hospital.
OtherTags: Deployed, GLA, Solar300, Tower Hamlets, V1

SiteDescription:
North Middlesex University Hospital has been serving the community for over a century. The first hospital buildings on the present site were built in 1909.

The hospital has expanded and modernised over the years, improving the medical, surgical, stroke and children’s services including a brand new maternity and neonatal unit. The new maternity unit is equipped with with state-of-the-art facilities and is among the best NHS maternity units in the country.

The Breathe London Node is located by the front entrance and serves to assess the exposure of visitors, patients and staff at the hospital.
OtherTags: Deployed, GLA, Haringey, V1

SiteDescription:
Newham University Hospital serves one of the most diverse populations in England. The hospital cares for more than 500 patients in its A&E department every day and is home to one of the largest maternity units in the UK with more than 6,000 births each year.

The hospital's state-of-the-art Rainbow Centre is geared up to meet the needs of its young patients and their families in a child-friendly environment. 

The Breathe London Node is located on a flag pole by the entrance to the A&E department where patients are picked up and dropped off.
OtherTags: Deployed, GLA, Newham, Solar300, V1

SiteDescription:
Whipps Cross Hospital has a strong reputation as a centre of excellence for various specialist services, including urology, ENT, audiology, cardiology, colorectal surgery, cancer care and acute stroke care.

Thanks to £6.7m in funding from Barts Charity, the hospital is making a series of improvements to its Maternity and Neonatal services to improve the environment and prepare for an increase in birth rates in its local population. This will include a dedicated clinical research hub for women's services.

The Breathe London Node is located by the main entrance near the car park to assess exposure for staff, patients and visitors.
OtherTags: Deployed, GLA, Solar300, V1, Waltham Forest

SiteDescription:
Charing Cross Hospital provides a range of acute and specialist services, a 24/7 accident and emergency department and hosts the hyper acute stroke unit for the region.

It is also a growing hub for integrated care in partnership with local GPs and community providers.

The Breathe London Node is located on a wall near the entrance on Fulham Palace Road.
OtherTags: Deployed, GLA, Hammersmith and Fulham, V1

SiteDescription:
The Royal Marsden Hospital opened in 1851 as the world’s first hospital dedicated to cancer diagnosis, treatment, research and education.

Today it operates as a specialist cancer hospital and National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) Biomedical Research Centre for Cancer, working closely with its principal academic partner, the Institute of Cancer Research (ICR).

The Breathe London Node is located on railings near the main entrance on the Fulham Road.
OtherTags: Deployed, GLA, Kensington and Chelsea, V1

SiteDescription:
Established in 1828 by William Marsden, the Royal Free's founding principle was that they would take in anyone who needed treatment – the first hospital in London to do so and the only London hospital to stay open during the 19th-century cholera epidemics.

In the 21st century, the hospital continues to lead improvements in healthcare and is proud to have some of the best clinical outcomes in the country.

The Breathe London Node is located in the busy pick-up and drop-off area by the entrance assessing exposure of staff, visitors and patients.
OtherTags: Camden, Deployed, GLA, Solar300, V1

SiteDescription:
Great Ormond Street Hospital is an international centre of excellence in child healthcare. It's mission is to put the ‘child first and always’.

Since its formation in 1852, the hospital has been dedicated to children’s healthcare and to finding new and better ways to treat childhood illnesses.

The Breathe London Node is located by the main entrance which receives 237,908 outpatient visits and 43,218 inpatient visits every year.
OtherTags: Camden, Deployed, GLA, V1

SiteDescription:
Guy's and St Thomas' is one of the busiest and most successful NHS foundation trusts in the country.

The hospital provides a full range of hospital and community services for people in Lambeth, Southwark and Lewisham, as well as specialist care for patients from further afield including cancer, renal, orthopaedic and cardiovascular services.

The Breathe London Node is located on a pole by the main entrance off Westminster Bridge.
OtherTags: Deployed, GLA, Lambeth, Solar300, V1

SiteDescription: At the end of November 2021 the reference monitoring site housed within the Broadway Theatre, which had been running since 1996,  had to be removed due to extensive long term refurbishment of the theatre.  Since no other closeby location could be found for the reference monitoring, it was moved just round the corner to Laurence House, and this Breathe London Node installed on the wall opposite the original inlet.  This will help continue the valuable long term data set from this location.

SiteDescription: Alice Model Nursery School is a small, warm and welcoming school in the heart of London’s East End.\r\nProviding a safe, exciting and inclusive learning environment for children full of stimulating, inspiring learning opportunities.\r\nAlice Model MBE was an East End social reformer who inspired the development of the Nursery. Developed from the Jewish day nursery she founded in 1901, it was for children of all religions, an ethos which continues to this day.
OtherTags: CHILL, Deployed, GLA, Tower Hamlets, V1

SiteDescription: Rachel Keeling Nursery School is a state maintained school in Bethnal Green, Tower Hamlets, providing nursery places for 3 & 4 year olds. Driven by quality with a highly dedicated multi disciplinary staff, children at the nursery engage in a wide range of learning experiences.
OtherTags: CHILL, Deployed, GLA, Solar300, Tower Hamlets, V1

SiteDescription: This is one of nine Nodes deployed at locations which are expected to have low pollution levels, but which are representative of large areas around them.  This provides balance across the network with many other Nodes being at higher pollution locations.\r\n\r\nWith the help of Tower Hamlets local authority, this node has been installed on Smart Street, near Meath Gardens Children and Family Centre. Meath Gardens Children and Family Centre is used by many parents and children in the community. It hosts health clinics as well as, baby and toddler groups.  The node will also be representing those living nearby and those using Meath Gardens Park.
OtherTags: Coldspot, Deployed, Solar300, Tower Hamlets, V1

SiteDescription: Stockwell Primary School is located in Lambeth for children aged two to eleven years old. As a school, they are committed to providing an outdoor environment for children that will provide stimulating and challenging learning. Such an environment supports both the curriculum and the extended school day programme.\r\nThis node is sponsored by the Mayor of London to measure the air pollution the children and staff experience while at school.

SiteDescription: Guy's Hospital was established in 1721 by philanthropist Thomas Guy. In 1974, the hospital added the 34-storey Guy's Tower and 29-storey Guy's House which is dedicated to improving outcomes of conditions such as Alzheimer's disease, stroke, Parkinson's disease and spinal cord injury. The hospital is part of King's Health Partners an academic health sciences centre, which is pioneering health research providing high quality teaching and education.

SiteDescription: This Node is located within the front playground at Martin Primary School, East Finchley, N2 9JP close to the A1000/High Road. SiteDescription: This Node is located within Redbridge's Business Low Emission Neighbourhood on Ley Street opposite the transport depot and is just north of Seven King's Primary School.\r\n\r\nOriginally located on the west side of LeyStreet , about 60m north of this location, it was moved to the east side to give a better location for the solar panel operation.

SiteDescription: This Node is in the middle of the Middlesex Street Estate, a Corporation of London housing estate comprising approximately 280 residential flats. \r\nResidents are of all ages, from newborns to centenarians and some have lived on the estate for around 40 years. The flats are built around and overlook a Podium; windows facing the podium are opened to provide ventilation to the flats. Within a short walk, the Estate is surrounded by major roads including Bishopsgate, Hounditch, Commercial Street and Aldgate High Street.\r\nResidents said that they are very interested to monitor the air quality 'as they are breathing the local air 24/7. This is in contrast to City workers who typically are in the area up to 8 hours a day and up to five days a week and many of them spend most of that time in air conditioned offices.’
OtherTags: City of London, Deployed, Solar300, V1

SiteDescription: This Node was deployed on Bedford Hill, a location chosen by the Wandsworth Environment Forum.

SiteDescription: Richmond is probably considered the main town centre for the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames and, despite many actions to reduce pollution, records the highest levels of NO2 in the borough. The vibrant George Street, is part of the main shopping area where shoppers and workers may spend several hours outside. This is the first of many Breathe London Nodes to be installed in the borough to try and give everyone an idea of levels of pollutant in real time.
OtherTags: Deployed, Richmond upon Thames, Solar300, V1

SiteName: Silvertown Tunnel access corridor  - Silvertown Way
SiteDescription: This Node has been placed close to a masterplan redevelopment area with high density residential development near to completion on each side of the access road (Silvertown Way).  \r\nA residential street canyon is forming on the northern approach road to the Silvertown Tunnel (which is currently under construction, due for completion in 2023). Once the tunnel is open, the traffic volume and the risk of exposure to poor air quality for new residents will increase. The monitor could report on pre and post construction air quality concentrations to feed into the decision making for any mitigation requirements.
OtherTags: Deployed, Newham, Solar300, V1

SiteDescription: This is one of nine Nodes  deployed at locations which are expected to have low pollution levels but which are representative of large areas  around them. This location not only represents the pollution levels at the allotments, with over 100 members spending considerable time there, but also represents the residents around and those using Poverest park and recreation ground.

SiteName: Horn Link Way j/w Peartree Way
SiteDescription: This node is solar powered and mounted on a lamppost in a roadside location.  The node is positioned here to review levels of pollution arising from both road traffic and fugitive emissions from industry.\r\nThe location is adjacent to part of the Greenwich Millennium Village, a strategic regeneration site within the Royal Borough of Greenwich. It received planning permission circa 2012 to deliver new residential units along with commercial, retail and community uses. The scheme has been built out in phases and has delivered a significant number of residential units that have made an important contribution to the annual housing targets within the Borough. The residential developments are bordered by long standing industry including, aggregate and cement works, and waste transfer operations. These industries supply an array of materials to support the construction sector and infrastructure projects in both Greenwich and the wider city.
OtherTags: Deployed, Greenwich, Quid Pro Quo, Solar300, V1

SiteName: Ceres Road, j/w Bannockburn Road - Bannockburn Primary School
SiteDescription: This node is solar powered and mounted on a lamppost to capture levels of pollution from road traffic in the vicinity. \r\nBannockburn Primary School is a diverse learning community located in Plumstead that provides the best possible support in enabling pupils to achieve their best. The school is spread across two sites both located within the Plumstead area. Pupils from Reception to Year 2 are based at the High Street site which is closest to where the node is located. The school has high aspirations for pupils, their families and the community of Plumstead. The Schools Vision is 'Growing Together, Learning for Life'.\r\nThe area surrounding the school site has been identified as having a high proportion of private rented housing, and in particular Houses in multiple occupation (HMO). With a localised Nepalese speaking community, the Council's Environmental and Housing Services are working closely with charity and community groups to better engage with this community on Environmental and Housing matters.
OtherTags: Deployed, Greenwich, Quid Pro Quo, Solar300, V1

SiteDescription: This node is solar powered and mounted on a lamppost in the town centre.  The node is positioned here to capture levels of pollution in this public open space. Sources of pollution include road traffic and construction works in the vicinity. \r\n\r\nBeresford Square is a pedestrianised town and market square in Woolwich in the Royal Borough of Greenwich. The square is home to a council-run market, dating back to the 1600s, selling general goods, providing bike repairs and food vendors with outdoor seating. The market operates six days per week and includes the location of the main gate of the old Royal Arsenal. The surrounding area includes the Woolwich Arsenal DLR Station, Beresford Street (A206), and the Woolwich redevelopment site at Royal Arsenal; a waterside housing and retail development area adjacent to the new Crossrail station.
OtherTags: Deployed, Greenwich, Quid Pro Quo, Solar300, V1

SiteName: Royal Hill, London, SE10 8RZ, adjacent to James Wolfe Primary School
SiteDescription: This node is solar powered and mounted on a lamppost at a roadside location adjacent James Wolfe Primary School. Local communities include both residents and students. The surrounding area forms part of the West Greenwich Low Traffic Neighbourhood and local resident groups have asked about the impact of this scheme on local air quality.
OtherTags: Deployed, Greenwich, Quid Pro Quo, Solar300, V1

SiteName: John Wilson Street, Woolwich, adjacent to St Mary Magdalene C of E School
SiteDescription: This node is solar powered and mounted on a lamppost at a roadside location adjacent to the A205 pedestrian subway and St Mary Magdalene C of E School on John Wilson Street (A205 South Circular). Local communities include residents and students. The surrounding area includes Ferry view Health Centre and the Woolwich Ferry Terminal. The node location marks the edge of the London Ultra Low Emission Zone (ULEZ) extension up to the South Circular which comes into effect on 25th October 2021.
OtherTags: Deployed, Greenwich, Quid Pro Quo, Solar300, V1

SiteDescription: The site is a kerbside location adjacent to a moderately busy road right in the centre of the borough of Hackney.\r\nAt this point, Amhurst Road is predominantly residential. The properties consist of a mix of residential blocks as well as some larger, older houses, many of which have been converted into separate residential units. Therefore, there will be a relatively high number of people in the area who may be affected by air pollution.\r\nAmong these are the residents of the Downs Estate. The estate includes 210 homes and is managed by a Tenant Management Organisation. The TMO has been instrumental in delivering improvements to the homes and this has included planting and landscaping works. Locating a Breathe London Node on their doorstep provides an opportunity to help further the interests of residents in their local environment and to see changes in air pollution over time. This we hope can encourage behaviour change and also help to raise awareness of their successes.
OtherTags: Deployed, Hackney, Solar300, V1

SiteDescription: In 2018 Islington started monitoring air quality outside every school in the borough using diffusion tubes, which provide monthly readings of the pollutant NO2. The tube for Whitehall Park School was located on Hornsey Lane and measured some of the highest pollution levels for schools in the borough, in contrast to modelled data for the school, and we think the Node will be a good way to help investigate further.
OtherTags: Deployed, Islington, Solar300, V1

SiteDescription: The solar panel node is located on the front of the Linden Children's Centre, next to the playground which is directly on Rectory Road.
